            <!-- Introduction -->
            <section data-scroll-reveal="enter from-left">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-green-700 mb-4">The Gig Economy: A New Way of Working</h2>
                <p>
                    The <strong>gig economy</strong> is transforming how people work and businesses operate. Instead of traditional long-term employment, this sector thrives on <strong>freelancers, independent contractors, and remote workers</strong> who take on short-term, project-based work. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    A staggering <strong>36% of the U.S. workforce</strong> is already engaged in some form of <strong>gig work</strong>, with estimates suggesting this number could rise to <strong>50% by 2030</strong> (<em>McKinsey & Company</em>). Companies are shifting towards more <strong>flexible work arrangements</strong>, leveraging <strong>digital platforms</strong> to connect with <strong>specialized talent</strong> worldwide.
                </p>
                <p>
                    But while the <strong>gig economy</strong> offers unparalleled freedom, it also presents challenges: <strong>job insecurity, lack of benefits, and increased competition</strong>. Whether you're a <strong>freelancer</strong> navigating <strong>gig platforms</strong> like Upwork and Fiverr, or a business hiring on-demand talent, understanding this shift is essential.
                </p>
            </section>

