            <!-- Section 1: The Core of Gig Work -->
            <section data-scroll-reveal="enter from-right" class="mt-6">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-green-700 mb-4">The Core of Gig Work</h2>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-700 mt-4">Freelancing and Remote Work</h3>
                <p>
                    At the heart of the <strong>gig economy</strong> are <strong>freelancers</strong> and <strong>remote workers</strong>. These individuals offer specialized services to multiple clients instead of working for a single employer.  
                </p>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-4">
                    <li><strong>Freelancers</strong> work independently, often managing their own schedules and clients.</li>
                    <li><strong>Remote workers</strong> perform tasks from locations outside traditional office spaces, leveraging digital tools.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                    While <strong>freelancing</strong> provides autonomy, it requires strong <strong>self-management, discipline, and marketing skills</strong>. The ability to juggle multiple clients, maintain a steady income, and stay competitive is crucial.
                </p>
            </section>
            <!-- Section 2: Platforms in the Gig Economy -->
            <section data-scroll-reveal="enter from-left" class="mt-6">
                <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-green-700 mb-4">Platforms in the Gig Economy</h2>

                <p>
                    <strong>Gig platforms</strong> serve as digital marketplaces where <strong>freelancers</strong> and <strong>independent contractors</strong> connect with clients. These platforms democratize access to work opportunities but also introduce intense competition.
                </p>

                <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-700 mt-4">Types of Gig Platforms</h3>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside ml-4">
                    <li><strong>Freelance Marketplaces:</strong> Platforms like <strong>Upwork, Fiverr, and Freelancer</strong> connect professionals with project-based jobs.</li>
                    <li><strong>Gig Platforms:</strong> Short-term work opportunities, such as <strong>Uber, DoorDash, and TaskRabbit</strong>, focus on flexible, service-based gigs.</li>
                    <li><strong>Crowdsourcing Platforms:</strong> Websites like <strong>Amazon Mechanical Turk</strong> distribute microtasks to a global workforce.</li>
                    <li><strong>On-Demand Service Platforms:</strong> Apps like <strong>Rover (pet care) and Handy (home services)</strong> provide immediate access to local professionals.</li>
                </ul>

                <p>
                    While these platforms offer convenience, they take <strong>commission fees</strong>, reducing earnings. Success depends on a <strong>strong portfolio, client reviews, and competitive pricing</strong>.
                </p>
            </section>

